---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="The story behind the Open GeoFeed Protocol — built by Matheus Matos, founder of Findera."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 pt-16 pb-24">

    <p class="font-mono text-xs text-emerald-400 mb-4 tracking-widest uppercase">About</p>

    <!-- Belief statement -->
    <p class="text-2xl text-white leading-snug font-medium mb-12 max-w-2xl">
      We believe the next computing interface is conversational — and the world is happening
      just around you.
    </p>

    <!-- Origin story -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I'm <strong class="text-neutral-200">Matheus Matos</strong>, and in 2016 I built a chatbot
        that answered questions about local businesses in natural language. You'd type
        "where's a good place for bacalhau near me?" and it would come back with a real recommendation.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        It wasn't a random bet. In April 2016, at F8, Zuckerberg opened the Messenger Platform
        to developers and declared that bots would replace apps. A new computing interface was emerging —
        the same kind of shift we'd seen with the personal computer and with mobile.
        Conversations instead of clicks. Text instead of menus.
        I believed it then, and I still do.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The product worked, technically. But NLP wasn't mature enough for the experience to feel right,
        and the Messenger bot wave crested and broke faster than anyone expected.
        I shelved it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The idea didn't go away. It came back in 2020 as a different shape: neighborhood feeds.
        Each place in the world would have its own activity feed — feed do Tatuapé, feed de Pinheiros.
        Businesses would post to their neighborhood's feed. Locals would read it.
        The monetization layer would be ads targeted by geopath instead of by device ID.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        That version died on the classic hyperlocal problem: you need users to attract businesses,
        and businesses to attract users. The unit economics of building a social network
        are brutal, and I wasn't willing to raise the kind of money it would take to win that game.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="border-l-2 border-neutral-800 pl-6 mb-12">
      <p class="text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed italic">
        "The core insight survived every pivot: local activity data is structurally missing
        from the internet. Not because it doesn't exist — it does, scattered across Instagram,
        WhatsApp groups, and paper flyers — but because it has never been published
        in a machine-readable format anchored to a place."
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- The shift -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">The shift that made it click</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        By 2024, LLMs changed the question. The problem was no longer "how do we build a consumer
        product around local data?" The problem became "why don't AI agents know what's happening
        near me?"
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity — they all struggle with the same blind spot.
        Ask them what's happening in your neighborhood today and you get either silence
        or something pulled from a review platform updated six months ago.
        The data they need doesn't exist in a format they can consume.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        That's the gap OGP fills. Not a consumer app, not a social network — a protocol.
        A standard for how local actors publish structured activity feeds, and how AI agents
        discover and consume them. The same idea from 2016, but finally in the right form.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- What OGP is -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">What OGP is (and isn't)</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        OGP is infrastructure. It defines a geographic namespace
        (<a href="/docs#subdivision-path" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300 transition-colors">SubdivisionPaths</a>),
        a registry that maps paths to content servers, and a feed format based on ActivityStreams 2.0
        with a single extension: the <code class="font-mono text-emerald-400">geopath</code> field.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        It's not a product. It doesn't have a dashboard, a login, or a pricing page.
        Any implementation that follows the spec can register with the public registry.
        Any AI agent that understands ActivityStreams can consume the feeds.
        The protocol is Apache 2.0 — permanently.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        The registry at geofeed.ai is the root — the DNS of the protocol.
        It doesn't serve content. It tells you who does.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Findera -->
    <section class="mb-12 rounded-lg border border-neutral-800 p-6">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
            <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">Findera</h2>
            <span class="font-mono text-xs text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-800 px-2 py-0.5 rounded">
              primary implementation
            </span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <a href="https://findera.com.br" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-white hover:text-neutral-300 transition-colors">Findera</a> is
            the reference implementation of OGP and the company that sponsors this infrastructure.
            It's a B2B SaaS for local businesses in Brazil — the product that makes OGP commercially sustainable.
          </p>
          <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Findera publishes structured GeoFeeds on behalf of its customers: local businesses,
            government entities, and events. Those feeds are registered with geofeed.ai and
            become available to any AI agent that queries the OGP registry.
          </p>
          <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
            The business model is straightforward: Findera earns recurring revenue from subscriptions.
            That revenue funds the OGP registry and the open protocol.
            The open protocol drives awareness and developer adoption.
            Developer adoption creates the ecosystem that makes Findera more valuable.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-5 pt-5 border-t border-neutral-800 grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
            {[
              ["Product", "Findera Presença, Conteúdo, Tempo Real, Alcance"],
              ["Pricing", "Free – R$149/mês per business"],
              ["Market", "Local businesses in Brazil"],
              ["Stack", "OGP server type: index, feed, signal"],
            ].map(([label, value]) => (
              <div>
                <p class="text-neutral-600 font-mono text-xs mb-1">{label}</p>
                <p class="text-neutral-300 text-sm">{value}</p>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Founder -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">The founder</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I'm <strong class="text-neutral-200">Matheus Matos</strong>, based in Alphaville, São Paulo.
        I've been building products around hyperlocal data since 2016 — the chatbot,
        the neighborhood feed, and now OGP. This is the version I think is right.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I trained the
        <a href="https://huggingface.co/geofeed-ai/subdivision-resolver-br" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300 transition-colors">subdivision-resolver-br</a>
        embeddings model — 1.17M training pairs, semantic resolution of Brazilian geographic names
        to SubdivisionPaths — and published it on HuggingFace under the geofeed-ai org.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        If you're building something with OGP, want to register a server,
        or just want to talk about the protocol, reach out:
        <a href="https://github.com/matheusmatos" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300 transition-colors ml-1">github.com/matheusmatos</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-6">Timeline</h2>
      <div class="space-y-0">
        {[
          ["2016", "Chatbot de recomendações hiperlocais. NLP too immature. Shelved."],
          ["2020", "Neighborhood feed with Findera Ads layer. Hyperlocal social network economics didn't work. Pivoted."],
          ["2024", "Findera relaunched as B2B SaaS for local business presence. LLMs change the context."],
          ["2025", "Open GeoFeed Protocol specified. Embeddings model trained and published on HuggingFace. geofeed-ai org created."],
          ["2026", "geofeed.ai live. Findera as primary OGP implementation. Registry open."],
        ].map(([year, event], i, arr) => (
          <div class="flex gap-6 group">
            <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
              <div class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-neutral-700 group-first:bg-emerald-500 mt-1.5 shrink-0"></div>
              {i < arr.length - 1 && <div class="w-px flex-1 bg-neutral-800 mt-1"></div>}
            </div>
            <div class="pb-8">
              <p class="font-mono text-xs text-neutral-500 mb-1">{year}</p>
              <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">{event}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Open source note -->
    <section class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-900 p-6">
      <h3 class="font-medium text-white mb-2">Protocol vs. company</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
        OGP is a protocol, not a product. The spec and the registry are Apache 2.0.
        Findera is the company that operates the registry and sponsors the infrastructure —
        but it has no special authority over the protocol.
        Any conforming implementation can register. Any agent can query.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Think of it the way email works: Findera is like Gmail — a major implementation
        of an open standard. geofeed.ai is like the DNS root — the shared infrastructure
        that makes the open standard useful. Neither owns the other.
      </p>
    </section>

  </div>
</Layout>
